{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}} {{Infobox military unit |unit_name= 76th Tactical Reconnaissance Group |image= [[File:76th Reconnaissance Group - World War II.png|250px]] |caption= Emblem of the 76th Tactical Reconnaissance Group |dates= 1942–1944 |country={{flag|United States|23px}} |allegiance= |branch=[[United States Army Air Forces]] |type= |role=[[aerial reconnaissance|Reconnaissance]] |size= |command_structure= [[Third Air Force]] |current_commander= |garrison= |ceremonial_chief= |colonel_of_the_regiment= |nickname= |patron= |motto=Our Observation, Your Security |colors= |march= |mascot= |battles=[[American Theater of World War II]] |anniversaries= }} The '''76th Tactical Reconnaissance Group''' is a disbanded [[United States Army Air Forces]] organization. It was last active in 1944 as part of the [[Desert Training Center]] at [[Thermal Army Air Field]], California.
==History== The [[group (military aviation unit)|group]] was constituted and activated in early 1942 at [[MacDill Field]], Florida as the '''76th Observation Group''' shortly after the [[United States]] entered [[World War II]].<ref name=Maurer141>{{cite book|editor=Maurer, Maurer|title=Air Force Combat Units of World War II|origyear= 1961|url= http://www.airforcehistory.hq.af.mil/Publications/fulltext/af_combat_units_wwii.pdf |edition=reprint|year=1983|publisher=Office of Air Force History|location=Washington, DC|isbn=0-912799-02-1|page= }}</ref> Its original [[squadron (aviation)|squadron]] was the '''24th Observation Squadron''',<ref name=Maurer161>{{cite book|editor=Maurer, Maurer|title=Combat Squadrons of the Air Force, World War II|origyear=1969|url= http://www.airforcehistory.hq.af.mil/Publications/fulltext/combat_sq_of_the_af_wwii.pdf |edition= reprint|year=1982|publisher=Office of Air Force History|location=Washington, DC|isbn=0-405-12194-6|pages=161–162}}</ref> which was joined a few days later by the '''23d Observation Squadron''' when the group moved to [[Key Field]], Mississippi.<ref>Maurer, ''Combat Squadrons'', p. 124</ref>
The group trained in [[aerial reconnaissance]] and [[close Air Support|air support]] techniques until March 1943 under [[Third Air Force]].<ref name=Maurer141/> It participated in [[military exercise|maneuvers]] with [[Second United States Army|Second Army]] until September 1943 when it moved to Thermal AAF and began participating in desert training in California and Arizona.<ref name=Maurer141/> In anticipation of this move, its existing squadrons were reassigned<ref name=Maurer161/><ref name=20SOSfacts>[http://www.afhra.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=9870 AFHRA Factsheet, 20th Special Operations Squadron] (retrieved Dec 3, 2012)</ref><ref name=Maurer330>Maurer, ''Combat Squadrons'', pp. 330-331</ref><ref name=Maurer348>Maurer, ''Combat Squadrons'', pp. 348-349</ref> and replaced by new units.<ref name=91NWSfacts>[http://www.afhra.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=15775 AFHRA Factsheet, 91st Network Warfare Squadron] (retrieved Dec 3, 2012)</ref><ref name=97ISfacts>[http://www.afhra.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=18204 AFHRA Factsheet, 97th Intelligence Squadron] (retrieved Dec 3, 2012)</ref><ref name=Maurer184>Maurer, ''Combat Squadrons'', pp. 184-185</ref> It was disbanded on 15 April 1944.<ref name=Maurer141/>
==Lineage== * Constituted on 5 February 1942 as the '''76th Observation Group''' : Activated on 27 February 1942 : Redesignated as the '''76th Reconnaissance Group''' on 2 April 1943 : Redesignated as the '''76th Tactical Reconnaissance Group''' on 11 August 1943 * Disbanded on 15 April 1944
